  "sections": [
    {
      "type": "grammarIntro",
      "title": "Connecting Actions",
      "icon": "⛓️",
      "summary": "Japanese has several connector words that link actions in time—expressing sequences (first…then…), simultaneous events (while…), purpose (in order to…), and non-exhaustive lists (things like… and…).",
      "whyItMatters": "Once you know these connectors, you can describe multi-step routines and plans naturally, rather than stringing together choppy individual sentences.",
      "youWillLearn": [
        "てから — 'after doing X, do Y': signals the first action is fully complete before the second starts",
        "まえに — 'before doing X': the verb before まえに always stays in plain (dictionary) form",
        "ために — 'in order to / for the purpose of': expresses a deliberate goal",
        "ながら — 'while doing': both actions happen simultaneously, done by the same subject",
        "～たり～たりする — 'do things like X and Y': lists a non-exhaustive sample of actions"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "grammarRule",
      "id": "rule_tekara",
      "pattern": [
        {
          "label": "VERB",
          "color": "verb",
          "text": "[Verb て-form]"
        },
        {
          "label": "CONNECTOR",
          "color": "connector",
          "text": "から"
        },
        {
          "label": "",
          "color": "modifier",
          "text": "～"
        },
        {
          "label": "MAIN ACTION",
          "color": "predicate",
          "text": "[Main action]"
        }
      ],
      "meaning": "After doing X, [do Y]",
      "explanation": "てから attaches to the て-form of a verb and means 'after having done X, [Y happens]'. The first action must be fully completed before the second begins. An alternative is [plain past] + あとで, which is slightly more casual and focuses on the elapsed time after the first action. Both patterns appear in the examples below.",
      "notes": [
        "てから emphasizes COMPLETION of the first action. 食べてから出かける means the speaker finishes eating entirely, then goes out — stronger than the simple て-connector.",
        "あとで can stand alone as an adverb meaning 'later': あとで話しましょう (Let's talk later).",
        "Do NOT confuse this から with causal から ('because'). In てから the から follows a て-form, not a clause-final plain or polite form."
      ],
      "examples": [
