        {
          "label": "MAIN ACTION",
          "color": "predicate",
          "text": "[Main action]"
        }
      ],
      "meaning": "Before doing X",
      "explanation": "まえに (前に) means 'before'. When it follows a VERB, the verb ALWAYS stays in the plain (dictionary) form—regardless of the tense of the main sentence. This is the most common error: students want to use て-form or plain past, but まえに always takes the dictionary form. After a NOUN, add の: 食事のまえに (before the meal).",
      "notes": [
        "ALWAYS dictionary form before まえに: 食べるまえに — NOT 食べてまえに, NOT 食べたまえに.",
        "After a noun: [Noun] の まえに → 試験のまえに (before the exam).",
        "Compare てから vs まえに: 食べてから (after eating) uses て-form; 食べるまえに (before eating) uses dictionary form."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "parts": [
