        {
          "label": "CONNECTOR",
          "color": "connector",
          "text": "ために"
        },
        {
          "label": "MAIN ACTION",
          "color": "predicate",
          "text": "[Main action]"
        }
      ],
      "meaning": "In order to X / For the purpose of X",
      "explanation": "ために (ため + に) expresses deliberate purpose. After a VERB, use the plain (dictionary) form: 勉強するために (in order to study). After a NOUN, use の: 健康のために (for the sake of health). ために is more formal and explicit than just using the purpose-direction construction (～に行く) — it stresses that the entire main action exists solely for the stated goal.",
      "notes": [
        "Verb before ために: always plain (dictionary) form — 話すために (NOT 話してために, NOT 話したために).",
        "Noun before ために: [Noun] の ために → 家族のために (for the sake of the family).",
        "Do NOT use ために with stative verbs that cannot be intentional (わかる, ある, いる). ために requires a deliberate, volitional goal."
      ],
      "examples": [
